      <hedline>
        <hl1>Why Do Polluters Get a Break?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Charles F Wurster letter contends Bush administration is violating Clean Air Act by permitting increases in pollution from power plants and other major polluters (Aug 28 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>We had better prepare for those hazy, hot and humid summer air masses to get worse.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>We had better prepare for those hazy, hot and humid summer air masses to get worse.</p>
        <p>The Bush administration is violating the Clean Air Act by permitting increases in pollution from power plants and other major polluters (news article, Aug. 28).</p>
        <p>The haze is made up of particulate pollutants, mainly from power plants and motor vehicles, which lower visibility, damage property and are a serious health hazard.</p>
        <p>Slow-moving summer air masses become especially dirty.</p>
        <p>They also are getting hotter because President Bush refuses to join the Kyoto Protocol, which would reduce carbon dioxide emissions, global warming and changes in the earth's climate.</p>
        <p>CHARLES F. WURSTER  Setauket, N.Y., Aug. 28, 2003</p>
        <p>The writer is emeritus professor of environmental sciences, Stony Brook University.</p>
      </block>
